or All Types\nHe said there is a large po\ntential market In the Washing\nton area for all types of air\nconditioning equipment.\n\"Central systems iheat pumpi\nand window units for Individ-1\nual rooms are available. Many\napartment houses and com\nmercial office buildings are re\nwiring for greater electrical\npower for air-conditioning in\norder that they can hold their\ntenants. If tenants can. they\nwill move into air-conditioned\nbuildings. Rewiring cuts down\nthe obsolescence of buildings.\"\nMr. Hills pointed out that\nair-conditioning service busi\nnesses have been sending out\nletters to their customeis since\nJanuary to have their air-con\nditioning serviced before the\nhot weather. But the recent hot\nspell caught the customers flat\nfooted.\nRichmond Reserve Reports\nSI 1.8 Million Drop in Loans\nThe Federal Reserve Bank of\nRichmond said today outstand\ning loans in the sth district\nfell sll\u00df million during the\nweek ended April 16. It said\nthe largest decrease. $7.8 mil\nlion. occurred in loans to brok\ners and dealers in securities.\nLoans for securities, loans to\nbanks and commercial, indus\ntrial an dagncultural loans\nalso dropped A partial offset\nwas provided by increases in\nreal estate and consumer loans.\nThe figures for Washington:\nloans adjusted. $546,425,000:\nreal estate loans $151,228,000:\nloans to brokers and dealers in\nsecurities $28.887 000: commer\ncial and industrial loans $226.-\n644,000: total investments\n$501,636,000; total assets sl.-\n380.039.000: demand deposits\n$972,952,000. and time deposits\n$295,082,000.\nAllen I* Named President\nOs Wholesalers Association\nJames E. Allen, president, the\nHenry Gilpin Co., wholesale\ndrug firm here, today was elec\nted president of the National\nAssociation of Wholesalers at\nthe annual meeting at the Ken\nwood Country Club.\nHe succeeds George W\nKauffman of the Kauffman-\nLattimer Co., wholesale drug\ngist of Parkersburg. W. Va.. who\nbecomes chairman of the board\nof trustees W. D. Jenkins,\npresident, Radio Supply Co,\nRichmond, was elected vice\npresident: A H. Johnson, presi\ni dent. A H Johnson Co., Pitts\ni burgh, was elected secretary\ni and Paul O. West, president.\nDoubleday-Hill <k Co. of the\nj South, Washington, was chosen\ntreasurer.\n1 George C. Webster, president.\nJ Wilson Supply Co. here, was\nj among those elected to the\ni board of trustees. Newly affili\ni ated national wholesale asso\n-1 ciation member groups are Na.\nJ tional Wholesale Dry Goods As\nI sociation. National Association\n5 of Electrical Distributors, Na\ntional Institutional Wholesale\nJ Grocers Association and Na-\nThis announcement it notan ojjer oj securitiesjor sale or a solicitation oj an ojjer to buy securities.\nNew Issue April 23, 1938\n$19,700,000\nPotomac Electric Power Company\n3%% Convertible Debentures due May 1,1973\n\nConvertible into Common Stoeh at 125 par abate\non and attar April I, 1959, connection priea being\neubject to adjuatment under certain circumitaneaa.\nTV Company hu iaauad to holdrri al ita autatandinf famAnn Slock trinafcraMa\noarranta, npirinf May t, IfSS, aaidanrinf ii|klt to aubacriV lor thaaa Dthoo\nhirai, al tV rata SIOO principal amount ol DrVnturaa lor aach 39 aharaa\nVld and al IV prira art forth Vlov. all aa mora fully art larth in tha proaporhu.\nDabcntuioa may ba ad or ad by tha onderwntera aa aol larth in tha proapoctua.\nSubscription Price 100%\nCopiej oj the prospectus may be obtained from any of the undtt \u201e,yned t\nwho are the underwriters named in the prospectus.\nDillon, Read Co. Inc. Johnston, Lemon Co.\nAlex. Brown Sons Folger, Nolan, Fleming-W. B. Hibbs Co., Inc.\nMerrill Lynch, Pierce, Fenner Smith Auchincloas, Parker Redpath\nFerris Company Jones, Kreeger Hewitt Mackall Coe\nRobinson and Lukens Rouse, Brewer Becker Birely Company\n1 k JL\nI\ns^^^^^E||||||||p*\nWILLIAM G. HILLS\ntional Frozen Food Distributors\nAssociation.\nThe National Association of\nWholesalers voted to back Pres\nident Elsenhower's plea for\nbusiness to get out and sell.\nBank of Silver Sprint\nTo Display Firming Cup\nThe Bank of Silver Spring.\nSilver Spring. Md., will shortly\ndisplay the Fleming Cup. which\nwas won in the District Bank\ners Association golf tournament\nat the Columbia Country Club\nby William D. Blair, chairman\nof the bank's executive com\nmittee.\nThe cup was presented Mon\nday night at the banquet of\nthe association by John Mc-\nCormack. cashier and senior\nvice president of Riggs National\nBank He was chairman of the\nassociation's spring meeting\nParking Officials to See\nFilm on Economy\nThe monthly membership\nmeeting of the Washington\nParking Association will be\nheld at 6:30 o'clock tonight at\nthe National Press Club. A film\nentitled \"Everybody Knows\nconcerning the economic situa\ntion and the wage-price spiral,\nprepared by the Chamber of\nCommerce of the United States,\nwill be shown. Presiding will\nbe L B Doggett. Jr., the as\nsociation's president.\n\nInvestment Analyst* Hear\nDiscussion on Chemicals\nThe Washington Society of\nInvestment Analysts today\nheard about the chemicals of\ntomorrow.\nThe featured speaker at the\nOccidental Restaurant luncheon\nwas O. C. Whitaker, assistant\nto the president of the Har\nshaw Chemical Co., Cleveland.\nHe said research is the answer\nto the problem of furtue chem\nical development.\nHe posed these questions to\nthe analysts:\n\"Can you see some of these\nchemicals of tomorrow? Can\nmetals be polymerized like plas\ntics to withstand higher tem\nperatures? What chemicals\ncan be found to process the\nleaner ores of the future? What\nchemicals will be used for inter\nplanetary rocket fuels? Can\nweather be made to order with\nchemicals? There are already\nindications that these areas are\npossibilities.\"\nMr. Witaker took his audi\nence on an imaginary trip\nthrough the firm's plant and\nviewed a movie of the labora\ntory. He said new crystals and t\nnow uses constantly arise.\nSafeway Report* Earnings\nHere Satisfactory In Quarter I\nSales ar.d earnings of Safe- I\nway Stores. Inc., for the first\n12 weeks of 1958 were satis-\nfactory, the annual meeting of\nstockholders in Baltimore yes\nterday was advised. The Board\nof Directors was re-elected\nMilton L Selby, a director and\nformer president presided and\nsaid he saw no reason why the\nsatisfactory trend should not\ncontinue for the remainder of\nthe year\nRENT\nATRUCK\nLOW RATES!\nHour, Day, Week, Long Term\nVans,Stakes,Panels,Others\nNATIONAL TRUCK\nRENTAL CO.\n1710-17th Street, N.E.\nLAwrence 6-5400\nCordiner Hits\nPanicky Plans\nTo End Slump\nSCHENECTADY. N. Y.. April\nj 23 (A*).\u2014The president of the\nOeneral Electric Co. cautioned\ntoday agalnat \u201cpanicky meat\nurea\u201d for recovery from the\nNation'a recession.\nRalph J. Cordiner. In a\nspeech prepared for the com\npany's annual meeting, said\nthat while unemployment In\nsome cities la serious. \"It Is\nImportant to keep the situation\nIn proper perspective\u201d and\navoid steps that would only\nprolong and complicate the\nrecovery.\n\"A swift and sure recovery,\"\nhe said, \"cannot be attained\nby sitting back and relying on\nGovernment stimulants, deficit\nspending, meaningless tax cuts,\ndeliberate inflation, or any\nother sleight of hand.\"\nThe solutions, he said, \"will\nbe found In a common effort'\nto all citizens U) work more\npurposefully, buy and sell more\nconfidently and build up a\nhigher level of solid, useful\neconomic activity.\u201d\nMr. Cordiner said that while\nthe company's first-quarter re\nsults for this yior were below\nthe levels of last year. It was\nstill the highest first quarter\nIn the company s history ex\ncept for the record year 1957.\nLife Insurance\nCompany Opens\nConvention Here\nWith 700 life Insurance men\nand their wives expected to\nparticipate, the four-day an\nnual convention of the Life\nInsurance Co. of Oeorgta got\nunder way lodty at the Shera\nton-Park Hotel.\nFeatured addresses will be\nRiven at tomorrow's business\nsessions by R. Howard Dobbs.\nJr., president of the company,\nand Rankin M. Smith, vice\npresident for field operations, j\nDelegates to the convention\nare top producers of sales and\nservice in life insurance. The\ncompany serves 11 Southern\nStates and has its headquarters\nin Atlanta. Officials said the\nfirm has more than $1.5 billion\nof life insurance in force.\nI\nCHICAGO\nLIVESTOCK\nCHICAOO Arm 2:1 iAh\u2014(USDAi\u2014i\nHoi* V.oon. slow early later trade:\nmoderately tells e very uneven butch\ner* weak ta 25 lower; rioted mostly VS 1\nlower sows *tead\u00ab ta mo\u00bbtlr \u20187.5 lower:\nall Interest In trade No 1 butcher*\nscarce, particularly weieht* under 275\nlb* nothine In receipts *uch a* told\nfor \"I SO on Tuesdav 2-3 190-225 lb\nbutcher* Cn.is-2n.TS. \u00bbeveral lot* 1-i\nthese weieht* 20.76-21 on: with tew\nsmall lot* I* also 21 on: :m head lot*\n1* 275 lb* uniform In trade <1.1(1-\n2-3 230-2*lo lbs 19 75-70 25: few I\naround 234* lb* to 2n 4n early 2.5\n\u2022Mn-'wn |h. 19 25-19 75 tew lot# 3s\n2\u00bbn-.lnn |b\u00bb I. on. 19 25: larter lot*\nmixed trade 4nn-Snn lb tow* 19.60-\nI. So few selected lot* 4no lb* to\n.5: limited volume 300-375 lb*\n1776-1950: sno.ssn lbs I6\u00abo-ia6o.\nCattle ld.oon. calve* TOO; elauehter\n*leer* moderately active steady to\nfully Stl lower some *ale* ofT a* much\na* ,5 on choice to prime, heifers ac\ntive mostly steady row* fully steady\nto stront: bulls fully steady vealer*\nteady viockert and feeders about\nsteady, hteh choice and prime slauehter\nsteer* 301*0.33 sn several loads serr\nate to hikh prime still unsold bulk\nchoice nicer* 2*.*5-30.50; tood to low\nchoice 25 nn-27..\\n; utility to low food\n21.00-251*0: hlkh choice and prime\nheifers 2*oO.:iooO. load prime 1.11*2\nlb welkin* tt .'loon eood to low choice\n25.00-27.75; standard to low \u00abood\n21 S4N2S.no: few utility down to 19 <MI;\ncommercial and standard cows 2oiMi\n-22 So: utility 1 *..\u2019>n-2\u00ab no cannrr*\nand cutters ISSo-tnoo utility and\ncommercial 21 50-23 So: ranner* and\ncutter* 17.410-21.5 n: tood and choler\nvealers 29 00.37 on; *t*ndard to low\ntood 77 fUi.2N.oO: cull and utllltv\n17 nn-7| on: several load* sood to\nrhotre SSO-725 lb feedlnt steers 26 00-\n7N 75.\nj Where There I* No\nI Compromise With\nI Quality Service\nIki\u00dfLii\nYOUR\nMONEY'S WORTH\nir SYLVIA PORTER\nNo Depression in Our Lifetime\nNot In our lifetime will we\nagain experience the horror ot i\na severe depression. Neither, 1\nthough, will there be a con\ntinuation of the easy economic\nlife of the past 15 years.\nThese are the twin cohclu\nilons of an Ideally timed book,\npublished today under the title.\n\u201cNo Major Depression In Our\nLifetime\" by A. W. Zelomek.\nthe nationally known econo\nmist who Is president of the\ni international Statistical Bureau\nand a University of Virginia\nprofessor.\nI couldn't agree more. What\nsent me to the typewriter after\nstudying his popularly written\ntreatise was one chapter in\nwhich he goes on the line with\nrecommendations on what to\nexpect in an era in which\n\"easy profits and high workers'\nearnings will no longer fall\ninto our laps.\" This is the\nsort of bread-and-butter stuff\nI'm sure you want to read.\nWhat. then, are some of his\nforecasts;\nTo businessmen:\nCompetition, already marked.\nwill become much more so.\n\"The kind of earnings we have\nexperienced since the war may\nnever again be experienced in\nour lifetime.\u201d\nGreat opportunities lie in\nsuch industries as electronics,\nelectrical and office machines,\noil, light metals, labor-saving\nmachines.\nLabor costs and prices of raw\nmaterials will remain high and\nthe challenge to you will be to\nkeep your costs down by Im\nproving the efficiency of all\nyour operations.\nInterest rates are In your\nfavor now. so don\u2019t wait too\nlong to arrange borrowing deals\nthat will be necessary in the\nnext few years.\nIf you don\u2019t Intend to stay\nin business for the next decade\nor 25 years, better sell or\nliquidate now.\nj To the wage-earner:\nWe're near the end of the ac\ncelerated rise in the wage struc\nture. Unions will concentrate\nOldeit Int eument Banking Firm in B athinglon, D.C.\nFor continuous S\nStock Morket Reports 2\nby nutomotic telephone MlLlll? 1 WW\nST. 3-5282\nFolgtr, Nolan, Fleming\u2014W. B. Hibbs ft Co.\nM(Mtf\u00abS NEW rO\u00ab\u00ab STOCK EXCHANOi\n725 15th Street N.W.\n1\nI,\nVl* YOURS...\nkr the asking\nIf souM like a regular look al markrl ronili\nlion* together with our opinion of various\nsecurities just phonr or write us You will\nreceive our Market Letter every other week\u2014\nit i* sour* without charge or obligation.\nOpen Thurtdny l mil 9:00 PM.\nAUCHINCLOSS, PARKER l REDPATH\nT2V l.\u00bbth Slrrrt, N.\u00ab NAtional 8-4J22\nMember Stork F.xrhange anil Other Leading Fxrhanget\nMORTGAGE\nMONEY\nownersf buyersJ brokers\nLOW COST LOANS\nATTRACTIVE RATES\nCOURTEOUS SERVICE\nPhone STerling 3-7700\nor visit any of our five offices\nPERPETUAL\nRUIIDING ASSOCIATION\ntDWARD C. BAITZ. Prmnhat C^JSSfr\nDOWNTOWN: ins c smi, n. w.\nANACOSTIA: iwo h*. no* rfEEHIQ I s\nRETHESDA-CHEVY CHASE: mb. ww.\nPRINCE GEORGES: niiMMmPh\nSILVER SPRING: onnn \u00abi cmhw st\n9\nmore now on a guaranteed\nannual wage and benefits.\nThe trend towsrd Increased\npension benefits still la In an\nearly stage. When you change\nJobs, examine the benefit*\noffered.\nUnless you are highly skilled,\nwith a scientific mind and\nbackground, stick to civilian\nindustries.\nThe opportunities In selling\nwill be greater than ever and\nservice industries will provide\na most attractive opportunity.\nTo the farmer:\nThe outlook for farm Income\ncontinues favorable.\nWhile the biggest advances\nin agricultural land values have\nbeen seen, the peaks have not\nbeen reached. Farm land values\nnear city areas will continue\nto gain. You still may properly\ngo into debt to Invest in land\nand expand your agricultural\noperations.\nEmphasize mechanization of\nyour farm.\nTo the homeowner;\nAlthough the rise in home\nprices has definitely slowed,\ndon't be discouraged The bot\ntom is not going to drop out of\nthe home market.\nThe demand for old houses\nwill remain comparatively\ngreat.\nTo the home buyer:\nTime Is now on your side.\nYou can be more cnoosy. press\nfor better terms, demand bet\nter equipment.\nWhen you buy Investigate\nTRUST I\n0)1 NOTES\nReasonable Rates\nPrompt Service\nlilt Will buy Second Trust Notts\nSecured ta Improved Property\nNational Mortgage\nInvestment corp\nmi N Y m\nthe advantages of both open\nend mortgages and prepayment\nclauses.\nTo the owner of stocks;\nThe long-term uptrend in\nstock prices has been only In\nterrupted this year. Much high\ner stock prices will be seen In\nthe next two decades.\nConcentrate on strong com\npanies in growth industries, but\nmaintain balance in your in\nvestments. Don't put all your\nmoney in stocks. Keep the pro\ntection of insurance, savings\naccounts, bonds, to some ex\ntent, mortgages.\nIDtslrlbulKl ISSN, hi Tin Mill hvndl\niil>. Inf All ruhli reserved!\nk Apartmgat*\nfcr'\u25a0 Caiasiirelil\nH i\nmortgage loans\nMortgage toon Corretpondont TK\u00ab\nCon*\u00ab\u00ab<ti(ut Mutual Lift Inturonti Co\nIM*n K Mr\u2022#! N.W BT. ft*?lt\nTAX FREE\nBONDS N\nAttractive Yields\nOur Bulletin\n\"How to Profit Through\nTax Exemption\"\nwill be sent on request\nJones, Kreeger Hewitt\nMember* New York Stock Exchange\nCefrlti 814$. 01. 7-ITM\n1625 EYE ST. N.W.\nffl Development\n\u2022Jill Loans\na lull Mongage loans for construction and permanent\n\u25a0\u25a0l! financing, with forward commitments, available\nat competitive rates. Take advantage of Weaver\n1H(I Bros, broad experience in serving builders\nmn\\\\ throughout Metropolitan Washington in both\nflMfllj large and small residentutl projects.\nS|| WEAVER\nHI BROS., INC.\u201d*\nJ|j|j fj* Washington Bldg.. District 7*1300\nRealtors Mortgage Bankers \u2014Since 1 <Bl\nMortgage lean correspondent for\nBHiI metropolitan life INSURANCE CO.\nEFFECTIVE SUNDAY, APRIL 27\nBALTIMORE OHIO ROUTE\nPASSENGER TRAIN SERVICE\nSITWIIN\nWASHINGTON\nand\nWILMINGTON PHILADELPHIA\nNEW YORK\nWILL BE DISCONTINUED\nThe last trips of these trains will be\non Saturday, April 26, 1958.\nWe sincerely appreciate the patron\nage of those who have used these\ntrains in the past and regret the\nnecessity for their discontinuance.\nBaO will continue its fine\nPASSENGER SERVICE\nBETWEEN BALTIMORE AND\nWASHINGTON AND THE WEST\nfrving:\nCumberland, Pittsburgh, Cleveland, Akron,\nTolade, Detroit, Chicago, Parkersburg,\nCincinnati, Louisville, St. Louis and inter*\nmediate points.\nCOMMUTER SERVICE ALSO CONTINUED\nCommuter service between Washington\nand Baltimore will be continued with\nadjustments in schedules to conform with\nDaylight Saving period.\nAlso\nALL FREIGHT SERVICE\nWILL BE CONTINUED\nNo change will be made in our modern\nFreight Services (including Sentinel, Time*\nSaver and Tofcee Service) between New\nYork, Philadelphia, Wilmington, Baltimore,\nWashington and the West and South.\nBALTIMORE A OHIO RAILROAD\nlinking 13 Groat Stotes with the Nation\nv* J\nSiegel Heads Loew's\nNEW YORK. April 23 <A\u00bb).\u2014\nLoew's, Inc., announced yeater\nday the signing of Sol C. Siegel,\n55. well-known producer, aa\nhead of M-O-M studio, largest\nIn the Nation. Terms were\nundisclosed.\nWhere food prepared\nto order it a time\nhonored tradition\nHOGATES\nCUSTOM\nCOOKERY\nAstor you art comfort\nably seated in our din\ning rooms overlooking\nthe curving sweep of\nth# Potomac, your\nluncheon, dinner or a la\ncarte dishes are cui*\ntom-cooked especially\ntor you. The nautical\natmosphere of tho\nSavon Seas it a Hogate\ntradition\u2014at i* custom\ncookery in the best\nihip'i manner. Gra\ncious and prompt serv\nice. Moderate prices.\n\u25a0I a Beit Seafood\nin Town\n0*\u00bb fit# Wotfrlrofif\nat 9tfi A Maine, S.W.\ni* Arl.rsQton ot\n4001 Wilton Blvd.\nAS*Nil Fell SAINING","height":"29203","width":"18592"}}
